    {
      "title": "Direct and indirect (reported) speech",
      "html": "<p><b>Direct speech</b> gives the exact words of a speaker inside quotation marks: <i>She said, \"I am tired.\"</i></p>\n  <p><b>Indirect (reported) speech</b> gives the meaning without quotation marks and usually shifts the tense one step back.</p>\n  <h4>Tense shifts</h4>\n  <table style=\"width:100%;border-collapse:collapse\"><tr><th style=\"text-align:left;padding:4px 8px\">Direct</th><th style=\"padding:4px 8px\">Indirect</th></tr>\n  <tr><td>simple present</td><td>simple past</td></tr>\n  <tr><td>present continuous</td><td>past continuous</td></tr>\n  <tr><td>present perfect / simple past</td><td>past perfect</td></tr>\n  <tr><td>will</td><td>would</td></tr>\n  <tr><td>can</td><td>could</td></tr>\n  <tr><td>may</td><td>might</td></tr>\n  <tr><td>must</td><td>had to</td></tr></table>\n  <h4>Other changes</h4>\n  <ul>\n    <li>Time and place words shift: <i>today→that day, tomorrow→the next day, yesterday→the day before, now→then, here→there, this→that.</i></li>\n    <li>Pronouns adjust to the reporter's perspective.</li>\n    <li>Questions become statements: use <i>if / whether</i> for yes/no questions; keep WH-words for WH-questions; drop <i>do / does / did</i>.</li>\n    <li>Commands use <i>told + object + to-infinitive</i>: <i>He said, \"Sit down.\" → He told them to sit down.</i></li>\n  </ul>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "Report: <i>She said, \"I will help you tomorrow.\"</i>",
          "a": "<i>She said (that) she would help me the next day.</i>"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Complex concord and grammatical exceptions",
      "html": "<p>Some concord (agreement) situations trip up even careful writers.</p>\n  <ol>\n    <li><i>Neither of / either of / each of / one of + plural noun</i> → singular verb: <i>Neither of the boys <b>is</b> here.</i></li>\n    <li><i>None of + plural noun</i> — plural verb: <i>None of the students <b>have</b> arrived.</i></li>\n    <li><i>The rich / the poor / the sick</i> — plural: <i>The rich <b>are</b> not always happy.</i></li>\n    <li><i>A pair of, a series of, a variety of, a bunch of</i> — singular: <i>A series of tests <b>has</b> been scheduled.</i></li>\n    <li><i>More than one</i> — singular: <i>More than one student <b>was</b> late.</i></li>\n    <li>Countries and titles ending in -s (<i>the United States, the Philippines, Wuthering Heights</i>) — singular.</li>\n    <li>Percentages / fractions agree with the noun after <i>of</i>: <i>Two-thirds of the cake <b>is</b> gone; two-thirds of the students <b>are</b> ready.</i></li>\n  </ol>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "Correct: <i>None of the water (is/are) contaminated.</i>",
          "a": "<b>is</b> — <i>water</i> is uncountable/singular."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Question tags, relatives and syntactic analysis",
      "html": "<p><b>Question tags</b> confirm or seek agreement.</p>\n  <ul>\n    <li>Positive statement → negative tag: <i>She sings well, doesn't she?</i></li>\n    <li>Negative statement → positive tag: <i>He has not left, has he?</i></li>\n    <li>Special: <i>I am, aren't I?; Let's go, shall we?; Open the door, will you?; Everyone is here, aren't they?; Nobody came, did they?</i></li>\n  </ul>\n  <p><b>Relative pronouns</b>: <i>who</i> (people), <i>which</i> (things), <i>whose</i> (possession), <i>that</i> (defining), <i>whom</i> (object). Non-defining clauses take commas: <i>My father, who lives in Kano, is a lawyer.</i></p>\n  <h4>Syntactic analysis</h4>\n  <p>Break a sentence into <b>subject + predicate</b>, then the predicate into <b>verb + object / complement + adjuncts</b>. Identify each clause: main (independent) or subordinate.</p>\n  <p><i>Although it was raining (subordinate: adverbial), the boys, who had planned the game (relative), continued to play in the field (main).</i></p>",
      "examples": [
        {
          "q": "Add a tag: <i>She has finished the assignment, __?</i>",
          "a": "<i>hasn't she?</i>"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
